"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ieuan ap Hywel was born about 1296, in Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Gwladus ferch Griffith. He died about 1361, at the age of 67."},"et":{"Abt 1296–about 1361":"umbes 1296–umbes 1361","1293–1342":"1293–1342","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1296–1361":"1296–1361","Abt 1296":"umbes 1296","1342":"1342","1330":"1330","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1361":"1361","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1293":"1293","about 1361":"umbes 1361","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Llwyn Dafydd, Llandysiliogogo, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Llwyn-Dafydd, Cardiganshire, Wales","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Wales","of, Deuddwr, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1296–about 1361":"noin 1296–noin 1361","1293–1342":"1293–1342","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1296–1361":"1296–1361","Abt 1296":"noin 1296","1342":"1342","1330":"1330","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1361":"1361","about 1330":"noin 1330","1293":"1293","about 1361":"noin 1361","about 1340":"noin 1340","Llwyn Dafydd, Llandysiliogogo, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Llwyn-Dafydd, Cardiganshire, Wales","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Wales","of, Deuddwr, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1296–about 1361":"environ 1296–environ 1361","1293–1342":"1293–1342","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","1296–1361":"1296–1361","Abt 1296":"environ 1296","1342":"1342","1330":"1330","1296":"1296","1340":"1340","1361":"1361","about 1330":"environ 1330","1293":"1293","about 1361":"environ 1361","about 1340":"environ 1340","Llwyn Dafydd, Llandysiliogogo, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Llwyn-Dafydd, Cardiganshire, Galles","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Galles","of, Deuddwr, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Ieuan ap Hywel est né environ 1296, à Montgomeryshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu 